First Impressions Matter

A Deep Dive into the Onboarding Experience of New Users on the Zerodha app

Research Goal

Zerodha after driving adoption and a considerable increase in its Market Share, intends to study the onboarding experience of its new users

Primary Research Questions Explored

a) Views and opinions of the new users of the app: their pain points, likes, dislikes, etc

b) What are the goals and expectations users have when opening the app for the first time

c) Identify opportunities for improvements to the app based on feedback from the new users

Since the case study is under NDA, I have omitted and altered images, parts of the research and design results based on my discretion. The information and data in these presentations do not necessarily reflect client's points of view.

Methodology

- User Research conducted 16 remote moderated interviews across 4 zones: South, North, East and West

- Target group comprising equal split of 2 age groups- 35 to 45 yo & 45 to 55 yo

- Tool used for discussions: UserTesting.com

- All of the participants were recruited via screener invitations, through the Zerodha user database

- Interviews lasted approximately 60 minutes

Initial Reactions to the app

An overriding assumption of the app being more sophisticated and secure compared to other trading applications.

Immense desire to explore and learn the functioning of the app

Various users want to have a better understanding of terms such as - good till triggered, margin intra day square off used throughout the application.

Despite the detailed write up on features, most users seek a video tutorial that trains and gives an overview of the app; most users turn to Youtube videos for the same

FIRST USE EXPERIENCE: Traders expect to be able expand their investment options vis-a-vis previous apps

Participants had differing experiences when using the app for the first time

They expected the app to be more user friendly

Traders want to see more investment options compared to the previous apps, like commodities and derivatives

Some Traders thrown off by the complexity of the advanced charting and technical analysis tools like- MACD, SMA, EMA, RSI etc

The user interface for placing orders was not immediately intuitive, requiring some learning to navigate efficiently

Positive User Onboarding Experience

Participants like how the app intuitively branches into different screen options depending on the user scenarios- Existing user or New User.

They liked being able to select dark or light mode.

Participants seem to miss the drop down menu that has the 'Customize' feature


DESIGN RECOMMENDATION: Since 'Customization' is a sought after feature, it is recommended to place it at a more intuitive spot/increase visibility

Welcome page

Users expressed varying preferences for accessing their portfolio or watch list upon logging in. Despite this, most indicated that they usually check their portfolio after initially looking at their watch list.

Some mentions about wanting to have an account overview page at the start, where they can review their account balance, recent activity, and overall portfolio performance.

DESIGN RECOMMENDATION:To accommodate diverse user preferences, consider developing a customizable dashboard that allows users to prioritize their preferred views. The dashboard could include options for users to set their default landing pageeither their portfolio, watch list, or a comprehensive account overview page.

User Assistance and Learning Resources

Given their long engagement with their previous apps, participants expressed uncertainty regarding the initial steps to begin using the app

There was a strong inclination towards learning about the usage by watching Youtube videos or conducting Google searches

A lot of the written documentation within the Help and FAQ screen was found hard to comprehend

DESIGN RECOMMENDATION: Interactive Onboarding Tutorial

Trouble understanding charts and trading jargon

While the app is considered more sophisticated than the apps formerly used, various users are also thrown off by the charts and studies

This problem was identified on several sections of the app, extending beyond just the Charts screen.

Examples: Kite Charting tools, MACD, VWAP etc

Most users are eager to be able to learn and use the tools

DESIGN RECOMMENDATION: Implement 'tooltips' or an in-app glossary feature that provides definitions in user friendly language for trading terms when users hover over or click on them.

Conclusion..

Overall Impressions

When new clients begin using Zerodha, they anticipate that it will offer more advanced features than their current trading platform.

They are generally patient with elements of the app that may seem confusing at first, due to its strong reputation and high regard within the trading community.

Additionally, clients are eager to learn and grasp how the app can enhance their trading skills.

Impact

Zerodha quickly embarked on a redesign project, focusing on refining the onboarding experience with more intuitive tutorials and improving the Kite interface for better navigation.

This overhaul encompassed updates to the user interface, improved order execution with more detailed order types, and enhanced support for Zerodha Varsity educational content.
